                    <a href="#">
                        <h2 class="post-title">
                            Promotions, and How to be Good at Them
                        </h2>
                        <h3 class="post-subtitle">
                            Our tips on how to become a better promoter and salesman.
                        </h3>
                    </a>
                    <p class="post-meta">Posted by <a href="index.html">CampusFly</a> February 20th 2015</p>

                    <p> Today, everywhere you turn somebody is trying to promote or sell something to you. Whether it’s your friend who is working on their 12th draft of their resume as they try to sell themselves to recruiters for jobs and internships, or it could the cheesy TV commercials for that dealership you drive by every day. People always have different motives for wanting to convince you to do something, and they can be as small as a personal favor to as much as taking your life savings, and some people are really good at making you do exactly what they’re seeking. These people are the geniuses behind incredible marketing campaigns. There’s a lot we can learn from these masters of marketing, which we can apply to our own goals and ventures. </p> 

                    <p> In order to be successful at promoting your objectives, whatever they may be, you have to be creative and confident. Being creative in sales and promotions is key. You have to stand out and you have to make people remember you. A great story that comes to mind is from an Episode of Shark Tank. Dave Mayer, a young entrepreneur and founder of Clean Bottle, faced the challenge that many entrepreneurs face: advertising his product. With little money and resources, Dave thought outside the box on how to get attention to his innovative bottle design. So he made a mascot sized costume of his bottle, put it on, and went to the Tour de France. With international media coverage, he started running alongside the bikers, fully-dressed in his bottle suit. He reached thousands, if not millions, of people and the best part is he did it all for free. This is just one example of thousands out there, where creative people think of new ways to raise publicity for their products or causes.  </p>

                    <p> Confidence is important in sales because you have to truly believe and embody whatever it may be that you are trying to get people to do.  If you are working in fundraising or philanthropy, you must have a meaningful and resolute reason as to why your audience should support your cause, and why specifically you are the person to best represent the cause. Confidence is especially important in the business world. As an early stage start-up, we are constantly pitching our business and ourselves. The confidence that we convey comes naturally from our passion for what we are doing. I am a big believer that confidence is built through experience and practice. If you want to be more confident, you have got to learn from your mistakes and practice your sales pitch, over and over again.</p>

                    <p>The reason we preach about successful promotions is because we are building a platform that helps event promoters and organizers accomplish their objectives. We are adding a tool that can bridge the gap between event promotions and millions of college students that had been previously difficult to target. We want to give event organizers the power to reach as many college students as possible, and we want to give students the opportunity to see all the events possible to them. Because this kind of platform does not exist yet, we urge all event organizer to become better event promoters and seek out new tools like CampusFly and make us an aide in perfecting your sales pitch.</p>
                </div>
